The paper discusses deep generative models and their ability to learn nonlinear manifolds in high-dimensional data spaces. This topic is closely related to machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision (cs.CV), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper introduces algorithms for computing geodesic curves and parallel translation, which are concepts from differential geometry and topology, suggesting a potential fit for the information theory (cs.IT) category. Finally, the experiments conducted in the paper involve real image data, further supporting the relevance of the computer vision sub-category.
